ere for my Profile"><img src="http://watchersrealm.virtualave.net/eq_sigs/eq_sig.jpg" border="0"></a><br></font></i><font face="Arial" size="2"><b>23 - Cleric | 56 - Beguiler</b></font><font face="Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular" size="2"><b><br></b></font><font face="Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular" size="2"><b>As one may say, "I know enough."</b></font><font face="Arial" size="2"><br></font><font face="Arial" size="1">- Lanys T'yvl - <a href="mailto:cakvala@fallenlegacy.com">Email</a></font></div></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ushallandra.showPublicProfile?language=EN>shallandra</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>h0x0r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(2/5/02 1:12:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1652.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Purple&quot; Server Ideas...</span><hr size=1> ROFL.  Interesting list.  My opinions:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 1. All classes/races have a base HP regeneration, comparable to Iksar at 60th.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
First, this invalidates part of the reason to play an Iksar or Troll character.  Secondly, a level 60 Iksar regenerates almost as much as a fungi tunic, standing.  I have used a fungi tunic for powerleveling and it makes you virtually immune to enemy attacks until level 20, and from 20+ allows a person to solo <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> far</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> effortlessly.  This destroys the need to group.  Everquest is about grouping.  Verant would never implement this, and I wouldn't support it if they did.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 2. Conning system becomes accurate. I.e if it cons blue at 55th, and isn't something named, (like a dragon in WW for example) it should be soloable one way or another by ANY class.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Classes are not designed to be equal.  Some can solo.  Some cannot.  Those that can solo--generally--are not as powerful or desired groups.  (i.e. a necro is a more desirable solo class, but warriors are more desired in groups.)  You can't make all classes good at soloing without making those classes who are already skilled at it more usefull in groups or else invalidating their appeal.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 3. Full exp while grouped, not lowering the amount you get per kill. No bonuses on zones/dungeons.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Um, no.  A person could have 3 accounts, kill mobs with just one and get equal experience for all three.  Talk about power leveling.  Experience distribution is good as it is.<br>
<br>
A different possiblity is that mobs could have a larger exp pool and give experience proportionate to the work involved.  This would have to take into account:<br>
<br>
1 - Damage dealt<br>
2 - Damage absorbed<br>
3 - Damage negated (healing, etc)<br>
4 - Miscellaneous effects<br>
<br>
This would, however, be buggy for characters such as enchanters who are defined as a support role and don't do damage as much as other classes.  (Thus, again, I feel the current system is fair.)<br>
<br>
A third option would be to give experience bonuses for actions performed.  In example, a rogue could get experience for successfully pick pocketing a mob.  A warrior would get a bonus based off the level of the mob.  A cleric could get exp for beneficial spells cast on party members (no exp for healing greenies, must be cast on a group member, and is prorated for the level of the target healed).  This might allow classes who do more to level faster, while not hampering the ability of other classes to level.  This is a common element in other roleplaying games, but I doubt Verant would ever take the time to implement it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 4. No armor/weapon/jewelry restrictions, other than what size will fit what races. Though maybe have melee type more adept at wearing plate class armors. Maybe STR dependant?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree, but only <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> if</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> there was a skill to associated with this (say, Plate, Chain, and Leather).  All characters can wear cloth and silk with no restriction.  Each class would have different skill caps on armor.  Some armors might require a certain skill to equip.  INT casters would <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> not</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> be able to cast spells while wearing any form of armor greater than cloth.  Priest and hybrid classes could be restricted per class.  (I.e. a ranger could cast spells in up to--and including--chain armor, while a cleric could cast spells in full plate).  Otherwise, this is too overpowering.  Why play a warrior if you can play a wizard who can wear plate armor and wield a sword?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 5.Nothing is no drop, nothing is lore other than unique drops from unique mobs. I.e FBSS, Fungus Covered Scale Tunic etc.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Um, no.  I disagree.  No drop is annoying, but with MQ it isn't an issue for quest items.  The only thing it does is keep people from farming items, and selling them.  Personally I think more items (fungi tunic, etc) should be made NO DROP, when they currently are not.  This would help reduce greed, as it simply isn't an option.  People are more likely to consider just how <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> much</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> they need an item, if its NO DROP, before taking it from someone else who can use.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 6.No exp loss from death, other than in PVP.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> would</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be nice, but in truth wouldn't work.  Unlike console games when you die you don't have to go back to your saved game.  Therefore if you didn't loose experience there is no detriment to dying.  There might be a way to get back 100% experience loss, but it should require effort.<br>
<br>
What I do think they should do is FUCKING remove un-dings.  The only thing worse than loosing experience is de-leveling.  Except for experience drains from undead mobs in some game genre (i.e. AD&amp;D), I don't know of any RPG where you actually loose a level when you die.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 7.PVP ability. I.e like Tallon/Vallon/Sullon.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It might be interesting if they could do this in the next expansion.  Use a DAoC approach, with the new lands being a middle-ground, allowing guilds, races, whatever to do battle and capture strongholds or what not.  However, there should be &quot;blue&quot; zones, so people who don't want to participate are not required to.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 8.Ability to choose spell lines for hybrids. I.e if you wanted a ranger, with the &quot;Cold&quot; based line of wizard spells (spells up until 44th or so to keep melees from doing comparable damage to wizards with spells), you would have to sacrafice something in return for it. Maybe STR, or 50% less HP or such.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Buhahaha!  A level 60 ranger could have 3 HP instead of 6 then <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Seriously though, an interesting concept.  I am rather disappointed at the loss of a melee/wizard hybrid.  I don't know how this <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> should</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> work, but it would be an interesting thing to see implemented.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 9.Instant-teleport pads to all major cities. I.e Like the Firepot Room in TD.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
FUCK YES!!!  Maybe you have to pay, but I support this 100%.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 10.Keeping ALL pets, illusions when you zone.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Agree.  Enchanters have the ability to keep illusions when they zone throug the use of an AXP skill.  This should be extended to pets as well, for major pet classes.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 11.Rogue's evade clears them from all mobs hate list.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Not sure if I can agree with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> all</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mobs.  More likely there should be a check for each mob (i.e. does the mob see the rogue sneak off, or not?).  Beyond that... unlike feign death, a mob knows when a rogue hides it is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> somewhere</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  It may not know where, but it would still be pissed at it.  When a monk feigns the mob believes its dead, thus can not truly perceive it as a threat.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 12.If you go invisible while running from a mob, and not being attacked, it clears you from all hate lists.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Agree.  This is, in my opinion, a bug.  If a PC looses a target when it goes invisible, the same rule should hold true for NPCs that can't see invis.  But, then again, since when have NPCs had to follow the same rules... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :/ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":/"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 13.Dying if you run out of food/water for a long duration of time.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Possible.  Then again, this is a lot of micro-management on the players part; micromanagement that some players just don't want to deal with.  At the very least, if this were to be implemented, the character should receive increasingly dire food/water warnings as they approach the brink.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 14.ALL items pickpocketable.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Hmm... well, any rogue than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> can</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> pickpocket a weapon while a mob is using it deserves my respect.  Maybe any non equipped piece of equipment (i.e. blue diamond).  But how do you pickpocket a piece of equipment in use?<br>
<br>
Also, if this were to be put into use, there should be a chance each PC within range can detect the pickpocket attempt, and what the rogue stole.  Otherwise, you'd have rogues on raids pickpocketing all the money gems and no one would be the wiser.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 15.ALL factions capable of being improved one way or another.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Agree.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 16.Charm permanetly charms mobs that doesn't resist the spell due to MR. (Not immune)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The game has this.  Its called Dire Charm.  The major charm classes (Necromancer, Druid, and Enchanter) can purchase the AXP skill.  It is dispellable though... unfortunately.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 17.No immune to mez, charm, snare/root/slow mobs, other than extreme MR.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Disagree.  Some mobs should be immune.<br>
<br>
Mezz/Charm:  Mobs flagged undead <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> should</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> only be charmed or mezzed by necromancers.  Afterall, they are not truly living creatures.  Anything defined as neither living nor undead (i.e. animated constructs) should be immune completely.<br>
<br>
